aa(lp17
VObviously, they're also women's issues, so I appreciate that,
p18
aVbut calling gender violence a women's issue is part of the problem,
p19
aVfor a number of reasons.
p20
aa(lp21
VThe first is that it gives men an excuse not to pay attention, right?
p22
aVA lot of men hear the term "women's issues"
p23
aVand we tend to tune it out, and we think,
p24
aV"I'm a guy; that's for the girls," or "that's for the women."
p25
aVAnd a lot of men literally don't get beyond the first sentence as a result.
p26
aVIt's almost like a chip in our brain is activated,
p27
aVand the neural pathways take our attention in a different direction
p28
aVwhen we hear the term "women's issues."
p29
aVThis is also true, by the way, of the word "gender,"
p30
aVbecause a lot of people hear the word "gender"
p31
aVand they think it means "women."
p32
aVSo they think that gender issues is synonymous with women's issues.
p33
aVThere's some confusion about the term gender.
p34
aa(lp35
VAnd let me illustrate that confusion by way of analogy.
p36
aVSo let's talk for a moment about race.
p37
aVIn the US, when we hear the word "race,"
p38
aVa lot of people think that means African-American,
p39
aVLatino, Asian-American, Native American,
p40
aVSouth Asian, Pacific Islander, on and on.
p41
aVA lot of people, when they hear the word "sexual orientation"
p42
aVthink it means gay, lesbian, bisexual.
p43
aVAnd a lot of people, when they hear the word "gender,"
p44
aVthink it means women.
p45
aVIn each case, the dominant group doesn't get paid attention to.
p46
aVAs if white people don't have some sort of racial identity
p47
aVor belong to some racial category or construct,
p48
aVas if heterosexual people don't have a sexual orientation,
p49
aVas if men don't have a gender.
p50
aVThis is one of the ways that dominant systems maintain and reproduce themselves,
p51
aVwhich is to say the dominant group is rarely challenged
p52
aVto even think about its dominance,
p53
aVbecause that's one of the key characteristics of power and privilege,
p54
aVthe ability to go unexamined,
p55
aVlacking introspection, in fact being rendered invisible, in large measure,
p56
aVin the discourse about issues that are primarily about us.
p57
aVAnd this is amazing how this works in domestic and sexual violence,
p58
aVhow men have been largely erased from so much of the conversation
p59
aVabout a subject that is centrally about men.
p60
aa(lp61
VAnd I'm going to illustrate what I'm talking about
p62
aVby using the old tech.
p63
aVI'm old school on some fundamental regards.
p64
aVI make films and I work with high tech,
p65
aVbut I'm still old school as an educator,
p66
aVand I want to share with you this exercise
p67
aVthat illustrates on the sentence-structure level
p68
aVhow the way that we think, literally the way that we use language,
p69
aVconspires to keep our attention off of men.
p70
aVThis is about domestic violence in particular,
p71
aVbut you can plug in other analogues.
p72
aVThis comes from the work of the feminist linguist Julia Penelope.
p73
aa(lp74
VIt starts with a very basic English sentence:
p75
aV"John beat Mary."
p76
aVThat's a good English sentence.
p77
aVJohn is the subject, beat is the verb, Mary is the object, good sentence.
p78
aVNow we're going to move to the second sentence,
p79
aVwhich says the same thing in the passive voice.
p80
aV"Mary was beaten by John."
p81
aVAnd now a whole lot has happened in one sentence.
p82
aVWe've gone from "John beat Mary"
p83
aVto "Mary was beaten by John."
p84
aVWe've shifted our focus in one sentence from John to Mary,
p85
aVand you can see John is very close to the end of the sentence,
p86
aVwell, close to dropping off the map of our psychic plain.
p87
aVThe third sentence, John is dropped,
p88
aVand we have, "Mary was beaten,"
p89
aVand now it's all about Mary.
p90
aVWe're not even thinking about John, it's totally focused on Mary.
p91
aVOver the past generation,
p92
aVthe term we've used synonymous with "beaten" is "battered,"
p93
aVso we have "Mary was battered."
p94
aVAnd the final sentence in this sequence, flowing from the others, is,
p95
aV"Mary is a battered woman."
p96
aVSo now Mary's very identity \u2014 Mary is a battered woman \u2014
p97
aVis what was done to her by John in the first instance.
p98
aVBut we've demonstrated that John has long ago left the conversation.
p99
aa(lp100
VThose of us who work in the domestic and sexual violence field
p101
aVknow that victim-blaming is pervasive in this realm,
p102
aVwhich is to say, blaming the person to whom something was done
p103
aVrather than the person who did it.
p104
aVAnd we say: why do they go out with these men?
p105
aVWhy are they attracted to them? Why do they keep going back?
p106
aVWhat was she wearing at that party? What a stupid thing to do.
p107
aVWhy was she drinking with those guys in that hotel room?
p108
aVThis is victim blaming, and there are many reasons for it,
p109
aVbut one is that our cognitive structure is set up to blame victims.
p110
aVThis is all unconscious.
p111
aVOur whole cognitive structure is set up to ask questions
p112
aVabout women and women's choices and what they're doing, thinking, wearing.
p113
aVAnd I'm not going to shout down people who ask questions about women.
p114
aVIt's a legitimate thing to ask.
p115
aVBut's let's be clear: Asking questions about Mary
p116
aVis not going to get us anywhere in terms of preventing violence.
p117
aa(lp118
VWe have to ask a different set of questions.
p119
aVThe questions are not about Mary, they're about John.
p120
aVThey include things like, why does John beat Mary?
p121
aVWhy is domestic violence still a big problem in the US and all over the world?
p122
aVWhat's going on? Why do so many men abuse physically,
p123
aVemotionally, verbally, and other ways,
p124
aVthe women and girls, and the men and boys, that they claim to love?
p125
aVWhat's going on with men?
p126
aVWhy do so many adult men sexually abuse little girls and boys?
p127
aVWhy is that a common problem in our society
p128
aVand all over the world today?
p129
aVWhy do we hear over and over again
p130
aVabout new scandals erupting in major institutions
p131
aVlike the Catholic Church or the Penn State football program
p132
aVor the Boy Scouts of America, on and on and on?
p133
aVAnd then local communities all over the country
p134
aVand all over the world.
p135
aVWe hear about it all the time.
p136
aVThe sexual abuse of children.
p137
aVWhat's going on with men? Why do so many men rape women
p138
aVin our society and around the world?
p139
aVWhy do so many men rape other men?
p140
aVWhat is going on with men?
p141
aVAnd then what is the role of the various institutions in our society
p142
aVthat are helping to produce abusive men at pandemic rates?
p143
aa(lp144
VBecause this isn't about individual perpetrators.
p145
aVThat's a naive way to understanding what is a much deeper
p146
aVand more systematic social problem.
p147
aVThe perpetrators aren't these monsters who crawl out of the swamp
p148
aVand come into town and do their nasty business
p149
aVand then retreat into the darkness.
p150
aVThat's a very naive notion, right?
p151
aVPerpetrators are much more normal than that, and everyday than that.
p152
aVSo the question is, what are we doing here in our society and in the world?
p153
aVWhat are the roles of various institutions
p154
aVin helping to produce abusive men?
p155
aVWhat's the role of religious belief systems,
p156
aVthe sports culture, the pornography culture,
p157
aVthe family structure, economics, and how that intersects,
p158
aVand race and ethnicity and how that intersects?
p159
aVHow does all this work?
p160
aa(lp161
VAnd then, once we start making those kinds of connections
p162
aVand asking those important and big questions,
p163
aVthen we can talk about how we can be transformative,
p164
aVin other words, how can we do something differently?
p165
aVHow can we change the practices?
p166
aVHow can we change the socialization of boys
p167
aVand the definitions of manhood that lead to these current outcomes?
p168
aVThese are the kind of questions that we need to be asking
p169
aVand the kind of work that we need to be doing,
p170
aVbut if we're endlessly focused on what women are doing and thinking
p171
aVin relationships or elsewhere,
p172
aVwe're not going to get to that piece.
p173
aa(lp174
VI understand that a lot of women
p175
aVwho have been trying to speak out about these issues,
p176
aVtoday and yesterday and for years and years,
p177
aVoften get shouted down for their efforts.
p178
aVThey get called nasty names like "male-basher" and "man-hater,"
p179
aVand the disgusting and offensive "feminazi", right?
p180
aVAnd you know what all this is about?
p181
aVIt's called kill the messenger.
p182
aVIt's because the women who are standing up
p183
aVand speaking out for themselves and for other women
p184
aVas well as for men and boys,
p185
aVit's a statement to them to sit down and shut up,
p186
aVkeep the current system in place,
p187
aVbecause we don't like it when people rock the boat.
