aVNow, the nature of the work that I do and my colleagues do
p231
aVin the sports culture and the US military, in schools,
p232
aVwe pioneered this approach called the bystander approach
p233
aVto gender-violence prevention.
p234
aa(lp235
VAnd I just want to give you the highlights of the bystander approach,
p236
aVbecause it's a big thematic shift,
p237
aValthough there's lots of particulars,
p238
aVbut the heart of it is, instead of seeing men as perpetrators
p239
aVand women as victims,
p240
aVor women as perpetrators, men as victims,
p241
aVor any combination in there.
p242
aVI'm using the gender binary.
p243
aVI know there's more than men and women, there's more than male and female.
p244
aVAnd there are women who are perpetrators,
p245
aVand of course there are men who are victims.
p246
aVThere's a whole spectrum.
p247
aVBut instead of seeing it in the binary fashion,
p248
aVwe focus on all of us as what we call bystanders,
p249
aVand a bystander is defined as anybody who is not a perpetrator or a victim
p250
aVin a given situation,
p251
aVso in other words friends, teammates, colleagues, coworkers, family members,
p252
aVthose of us who are not directly involved in a dyad of abuse,
p253
aVbut we are embedded in social, family, work, school,
p254
aVand other peer culture relationships
p255
aVwith people who might be in that situation.
p256
aVWhat do we do? How do we speak up? How do we challenge our friends?
p257
aVHow do we support our friends?
p258
aVBut how do we not remain silent in the face of abuse?
p259
aa(lp260
VNow, when it comes to men and male culture,
p261
aVthe goal is to get men who are not abusive to challenge men who are.
p262
aVAnd when I say abusive, I don't mean just men who are beating women.
p263
aVWe're not just saying a man whose friend is abusing his girlfriend
p264
aVneeds to stop the guy at the moment of attack.
p265
aVThat's a naive way of creating a social change.
p266
aVIt's along a continuum, we're trying to get men to interrupt each other.
p267
aVSo, for example, if you're a guy and you're in a group of guys
p268
aVplaying poker, talking, hanging out, no women present,
p269
aVand another guy says something sexist or degrading or harassing about women,
p270
aVinstead of laughing along or pretending you didn't hear it,
p271
aVwe need men to say, "Hey, that's not funny.
p272
aVthat could be my sister you're talking about,
p273
aVand could you joke about something else?
p274
aVOr could you talk about something else?
p275
aVI don't appreciate that kind of talk."
p276
aVJust like if you're a white person
p277
aVand another white person makes a racist comment, you'd hope, I hope,
p278
aVthat white people would interrupt that racist enactment
p279
aVby a fellow white person.
p280
aVJust like with heterosexism, if you're a heterosexual person
p281
aVand you yourself don't enact harassing or abusive behaviors
p282
aVtowards people of varying sexual orientations,
p283
aVif you don't say something in the face of other heterosexual people doing that,
p284
aVthen, in a sense, isn't your silence a form of consent and complicity?
p285
aa(lp286
VWell, the bystander approach is trying to give people tools
p287
aVto interrupt that process and to speak up and to create a peer culture climate
p288
aVwhere the abusive behavior will be seen as unacceptable,
p289
aVnot just because it's illegal, but because it's wrong
p290
aVand unacceptable in the peer culture.
p291
aVAnd if we can get to the place where men
p292
aVwho act out in sexist ways will lose status,
p293
aVyoung men and boys who act out in sexist
p294
aVand harassing ways towards girls and women,
p295
aVas well as towards other boys and men,
p296
aVwill lose status as a result of it, guess what?
p297
aVWe'll see a radical diminution of the abuse.
p298
aVBecause the typical perpetrator is not sick and twisted.
p299
aVHe's a normal guy in every other way, isn't he?
p300
aa(lp301
VNow, among the many great things that Martin Luther King
p302
aVsaid in his short life was,
p303
aV"In the end, what will hurt the most is not the words of our enemies
p304
aVbut the silence of our friends."
p305
aVIn the end, what will hurt the most is not the words of our enemies
p306
aVbut the silence of our friends.
p307
aVThere's been an awful lot of silence in male culture
p308
aVabout this ongoing tragedy of men's violence
p309
aVagainst women and children, hasn't there?
p310
aVThere's been an awful lot of silence.
p311
aVAnd all I'm saying is that we need to break that silence,
p312
aVand we need more men to do that.
